-- S. African Stocks: AngloGold, BHP, Gold Fields, Sea Kay Move
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-24T10:52:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-24/south-african-stocks-anglo-bhp-billiton-gold-fields-sasol.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  declined 90.25, or 0.3 percent, to 32,037.06, taking
the year-to-date gain to 16 percent at the 12 p.m. close in
Johannesburg. The market closed early for the Christmas holiday.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest producer
of the metal, snapped days of three days of losses, rising 3.90
rand, or 1.2 percent, to 326.80 rand. Gold advanced for the
first time in three days as concern that the European sovereign-
debt crisis will continue spurs investors’ demand for a haven.
 Gold Fields Ltd. , the second-largest producer, increased for the
first time in four days, rallying 90 cents, or 0.8 percent, to
119.41 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, dropped 2.57 rand, or 1 percent, to 267.51 rand. The
company said it had entered into an arrangement with an
independent entity that will to buy back the mining company’s
shares on BHP Billiton’s behalf until Feb. 15, the day before it
releases first-half results.  Marshall Monteagle Holdings Societe Anonyme  (MTE SJ), an
investment company with interests in shipping and agriculture,
increased for the first time since Dec. 13, adding 40 cents, or
4.2 percent, to 10 rand. The company said earnings per share for
the year through September probably rose more than fourfold
compared with a year earlier.  Sea Kay Holdings Ltd.  (SKY SJ), a builder of low-cost
houses, declined for the first day in four, losing 1 cent, or 11
percent, to 8 cents. Sea Kay said its loss for the year through
June widened to 239.17 million rand ($35 million) compared with
profit of 25.2 million rand a year earlier.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
